 git? ==> the content tracker


git init ==>  Create an empty Git repository 
git add ==>  Adds files in the to the staging area for Git(git add <fileName>)
git add . / git add -a ==> to add all file in the staging area

git status ==>  returns the current state of the repository
git commit -m "myMessage"  ==> Record changes to the repository


git checkout ==> Switch branches or Checking out a branch updates and record all new commits on that branch.

git diff ==> Show changes between commits, commit and working tree 
git log ==> shows commit logs

git branch ==> are effectively a pointer to a snapshot of your changes
git merge ==> Join two or more development histories together


git pull ==>  update the local version of a repository from a remote
git push ==>  upload local repository content to a remote repository.


git add remote url ==> create a new connection record to a remote repository
git remote -v ==>  manages the set of remotes that you are tracking with your local repository(fetch , push)

git clone ==> to copy/ downloads an existing Git repository to your local computer
git --help 